### **GranTON Q2 Quarterly Report**

# ![][image1]2025 Q2 Tokamak Network(TON) Quarterly Report : 4/1 \~ 6/30

### **Highlight**

In Q2 2025, the Tokamak Network’s GranTON program accelerated the development of its modular Layer 2 ecosystem. From scalable staking protocols and governance platforms to appchain SDKs and privacy-preserving rollups, each project showed strong alignment with Tokamak’s mission to empower builders with developer-first, customizable infrastructure.

Decentralized features like DAO agenda registration, Sybil resistance, and zero-knowledge proof tools moved closer to production-ready maturity, while educational and public-facing resources helped foster transparency and accessibility for the broader Ethereum community.

# **1\. Q2 2025 Grant Project Report**

# **1.1 Introduction**

The GranTON program continues to fund high-impact projects that contribute to Tokamak Network’s decentralized infrastructure. In Q2, selected teams advanced components critical to Tokamak’s evolution into a developer-first L2 platform—covering staking security, governance tooling, modular rollup SDKs, and ZK-based privacy systems. This report summarizes their Q2 goals, outputs, challenges, and next steps.

# **1.2 Developing Decentralized Staking and Governance([Overview](https://tokamak.notion.site/49e44e989c514bd683e077c01cc8f143?pvs=25)).**

### **Goal**

Project ECO's final goals are twofold:

* Design and implement Tokamak Network's staking system—including slashing mechanisms and fast withdrawals—as specified in the [whitepaper.](https://github.com/tokamak-network/papers/blob/master/cryptoeconomics/tokamak-cryptoeconomics-en.md) This will enhance L2 security, increase TON and staked TON utility, and strengthen the Tokamak Network DAO's decentralization and security.  
* Deploy the Simple Staking & DAO community version and discontinue the hosted frontend and backend services while minimizing any resulting TON withdrawals

### **Key Features**

* **Two types of staking service**  
  * Launch Staking V2 and implement the community version of it.  
* **DAO V2 Governance Platform Prototype**  
  * Built community-ready DAO interface with proposal voting, metadata registration, and member management.  
* **DAO Agenda Metadata Automation**  
  * Launched GitHub-based agenda registration system with auto-verification and PR workflow.

# **1.3 Advancing Developer-Centric Appchain Infrastructure([Overview](https://tokamak.notion.site/1433390669554ae5b09e400f4c9c0fd4?pvs=25)).**

### **Goal**

As part of the Tokamak Rollup Hub (TRH) initiative, the project focuses on delivering reusable infrastructure components for rollup-based applications. In Q2, the primary objective was to develop and test a modular SDK capable of deploying a Layer 2 Testnet chain with TON as the native gas token. The SDK also supports integration of essential components such as a bridge and block explorer. This allows anyone to quickly deploy a testnet chain and experiment with its features using TON as the native token.

### **Key Features**

* **Developed a modular SDK capable of deploying a Layer 2 Testnet chain with TON as the native gas token.**

* **SDK now supports testnet registration of new appchains as Tokamak DAO candidates via Staking v2.**

* **Designed the system to be reusable by other Tokamak ecosystem projects.**

# **1.4 Developing Zero-Knowledge Proof-Based On-Demand Rollups([Overview](https://medium.com/tokamak-network/project-tokamak-zk-evm-67483656fd21)).**

### **Goal**  The goal of this quarter was to complete and release “Tokamak zk-EVM: Practice,” a practical zero-knowledge proof tool that allows users to generate proofs for Ethereum transactions with just a few clicks. The system is optimized to run on standard hardware and includes a new consensus layer based on multi-party computation to improve future security.

### **Key Features**

* **A playground for Tokamak zk-EVM has been released**  
  * We help users apply ZKP to their transactions with just a few clicks.   
  * Install and run an easy-to-use app we provide. ([link to download](https://github.com/tokamak-network/Tokamak-zk-EVM-playgrounds/tree/main/packages/playground-hub#tokamak-zk-evm-playground-user-guide))  
  * Minimal system requirements: 16GB RAM.  
  * A CUDA-enabled GPU will provide a better experience.  
* **Tokamak zk-EVM implementation**  
  * We succeeded in implementing the backend protocol of Tokamak zk-EVM.  
  * The implementation is highly optimized based on ICICLE’s GPU library.  
  * 

### **Q2 Outputs**

* **Tokamak zk-EVM: Practice**  
  * Implementation of backend main protocol ([github](https://github.com/tokamak-network/Tokamak-zk-EVM/tree/main/packages/backend))  
  * Implementation of secure multi-party computation (MPC) setup ([github](https://github.com/tokamak-network/Tokamak-zk-EVM/tree/main/packages/backend/setup/mpc-setup))  
  * Implementation of playground—a graphic user interface ([github](https://github.com/tokamak-network/Tokamak-zk-EVM-playgrounds/tree/main/packages/playground-hub))  
* **Public activity**  
  * Presented a talk at EthCluj25 ([official post](https://www.linkedin.com/posts/ethereumcluj_ethcluj-ethereum-activity-7330834737814532097-j38d?utm_source=share&utm_medium=member_desktop&rcm=ACoAAEyPpogBgwi21mpkk-okpNIGLsp7Ni0Qm_k))  
  * Presented a talk at EthCC\[8\] ([official post](https://ethcc.io/speakers/jehyuk-jang))

**Q2 Summary and Next Steps**

In Q2, the team successfully completed the first version of Tokamak zk-EVM: Practice, a practical tool that allows users to generate zero-knowledge proofs for Ethereum transactions on machines with GPU and 16GB RAM. The system also includes a pre-SNARK consensus protocol based on secure multi-party computation to enhance the security of future services. In the next phase, the team plans to design a Layer 2 architecture based on Tokamak zk-EVM.

# **1.5 Developing a Sybil-Resistance System for Decentralized Applications([Overview](https://tokamak.notion.site/03cc941223844f30ba4473e98b1275a7?pvs=25)).**

### **Goal**

The main goal of this quarter was to develop and test a Sybil resistance system that can detect and score potential Sybil accounts based on their on-chain behavior. The team aimed to create a reliable scoring algorithm and make it accessible via Snapshot for use by third-party applications.

### **Key Features**

* **Sybil Resistance v1 – On-Chain Behavior Scoring & Snapshot Integration**  
  * The team implemented a system that analyzes user behavior on-chain to detect potential Sybil accounts and assigns each a score. This score can be used in governance tools like Snapshot to allow or restrict participation. The system includes a working smart contract, a testnet deployment, and an integration with Snapshot.

### **Q2 Outputs**

* **Sybil Scoring Algorithm**  
  * Implemented scoring algorithm in Go for use in sequencer package.([link](https://github.com/tokamak-network/tokamak-sybil-resistance-mvp/blob/jjamie65-patch-1/circuits/scoringalg.go))  
* **Testnet Deployment & Sequencer**  
  * Got sequencer package running smoothly including forging batches to the  
    contract on testnet.([link](https://github.com/tokamak-network/syb-sequencer))  
* **Snapshot Integration**  
  * Integrated our contract with Snapshot for use by 3rd parties.([link](https://github.com/tokamak-network/tokamak-sybil-resistance-mvp/tree/develop/contracts))  
* **Frontend Interface & API**  
  * Wrote API and a frontend to make it easy to explore the full state data.([link](https://github.com/tokamak-network/syb-sequencer/tree/develop/sequencer/db/historydb))

**Q2 Summary and Next Steps**

In Q2, the SYB team completed internal development and testing of key components for a Sybil resistance system, including the scoring algorithm, testnet deployment, and Snapshot integration. The system remains under internal review, and no plans for public release have been finalized.

# **1.7 Summary**

In Q2 2025, core components of the Tokamak Network’s Layer 2 ecosystem were progressively released for public use. Key outputs included the completion of the Staking V2 smart contract, its internal audit, supporting blog content, and the initial version of a community-based DAO governance tool. A deployment SDK (v1) was launched alongside a rebranded website and prototype UI. The zk-EVM prototype was also released, featuring a lightweight proof generation tool that runs on standard hardware and includes a multi-party computation–based security layer. In addition, a Sybil resistance system was internally tested, including a scoring algorithm, Snapshot contract integration, frontend, and state explorer—several of which are nearing public launch.

This quarter marked a tangible shift, as multiple GranTON projects delivered usable tools or prototypes that solidify Tokamak’s modular infrastructure for scalable decentralized applications.

**4\. Community**

#### **4.1 FAQ**

These are some of the FAQs from the community. Please check the section below.

* **What does it mean that the zk-EVM can convert random Ethereum transactions to zk-proofs?**

1. This milestone shows that Tokamak’s zk-EVM has reached the stage where arbitrary Ethereum transactions can be transformed into zero-knowledge proofs. All that is required is to provide a transaction as input to the system. The underlying theory of Tokamak zk-SNARK— the cryptographic engine powering the zk-EVM—ensures that the transaction can be faithfully replaced by a corresponding proof. This marks a major step toward building a fully functional zk-rollup, where transaction integrity is verifiable without revealing sensitive data. This advancement brings Tokamak closer to offering privacy-preserving execution of Ethereum smart contracts.  
* **What is the Tokamak Rollup Hub and why is it important?**

1. The **Tokamak Rollup Hub** (TRH) is an **on-demand Layer 2 infrastructure platform** designed to enable **seamless deployment** and **end-to-end lifecycle managemen**t of Appchains. It aims to serve as a comprehensive hub that not only showcases our research outputs but also offers **essential tools** for integration and smooth network operations by deployers. TRH supports various **modular rollup technologies** and **developer-friendly SDKs**. In this report, we would like to mention the successful completion of the **second round of testing for SDKv1**, marking significant progress toward a **community-ready release**.

* **Why do we need a Rollup Hub? Aren’t there already many Layer 2 solutions?**

1. The Tokamak Rollup Hub is more than just another **Layer 2 solution** — it’s a **flexible platform** that empowers developers to deploy **modular Layer 2 Appchains**, supporting various rollup types like **Optimistic and ZK Rollups**. It enables the integration of components such as bridges, explorers, cross-trade module, random number generator, fraud proofs, and data availability layers based on specific project needs, allowing for **fully customized rollup chains**. Deployed chains can be **self-managed** by deployers on their own AWS infrastructure (with support for more environments planned), removing the dependency on third-party RaaS providers.  
2. Instead of offering a one-size-fits-all rollup, Tokamak Rollup Hub provides the flexibility to **launch and manage your own rollup architecture** tailored to your application’s needs. In that sense, it’s not just a rollup — it’s a **platform for building rollups**.
